I miss the Nyonya on 8th Avenue back in the day but this place is still solid and has my favorite dishes.  I don’t know if Nyonya is still associated with Penang but over 20yrs ago, I was told Nyonya was an off shoot of Penang which just exploded in popularity in Manhattan and Queens way way back.  Must try items:  Roti canai - delicious hot/fresh roti bread with chicken curry dip Kang Kung Belacan - delicious vegetable stir fry with I think a sambal sauce Beef rendang - braised beef in a deep curry like sauce Chow Kueh Teow - a stir fried soft noodle chow mein/fun type dish Nasi Lemak - it’s a combo dish and I think a National dish of Malaysia.  More experienced/adventurous options:  Asam Laksa Roti Telur Nasi Goreng  Malaysian food is on my rotation at lease once a week and I’m so surprised people have Thai food on their regular rotation but not Malaysian?

I boycotted this place for a few years because we had a bad customer experience with the boss lady. No joke. She can be real unpleasant at times. However, we ran out of places to eat locally, and finally decided to give this place another go.  The food here is decent but I remember it being more tasty. If you're allergic to shrimp, look elsewhere because they put shrimp in everything; even though I requested, nicely, no shrimp - or my sister's bf will die.  Our go to dishes are the roti canai (Indian pancake), hainanese chicken, and a surang burung (taro nest).  The same lady took our order. I learned that if you're quick with your decisions, she is tolerable. I'm sorry, I know she may be somebody's mother. Just be sure of what you want! Or she will get impatient. Service can definitely improve, but we came in with a group of 7 and left with 6 full stomachs and 1 less full, but as long as his airway is clear, no complaints!  PS. If they recommend the fish, let the waitress know - "you good".

THIS is probs the best thing you can get here. The sauce that comes with this dish is sooooo gooood. You can probs get an extra loaf of bread, eat it with the sauce, and be GOOD. Once again, the only restaurant of its kind in the area decides to take advantage of its customers' cravings.  It really is a shame considering it does have potential.  I ordered my usual roti canai(Indian pancake) and char kway teow(rice strip noodles) with shrimp.  The noodles had surprising wok hay, which is Cantonese for the sweet spot reached when cooking food in a wok on high heat.  The char kway teow had 5 shrimp in it.  I counted because that's how many I spit out.  You can tell when shrimp isn't fresh when it is so chalky that it melts in your mouth.  I gave them the benefit of the doubt and tried all of them before saying anything.  Out of all the staff that waited on us, only one had a friendly demeanor.  The rest had the "if you don't like it, take a hike" attitude. I happened to flag one of the nasty ones down, explained the situation, and proceeded to hear the funniest explanation.  She said that ALL the seafood is shipped fresh daily and that it should all be fresh. In fact, when I pointed at the chewed up shrimp I spat out, she said there's always bound to be one that's spoiled.  When I countered that none were edible, thereby disproving her previous statement, she shrugged her shoulders and strutted away.  Way to go, I love watching people walk away from me.  Now watch as I never return to your restaurant.

The food was abysmal, and standing at 165lbs I was not even close to full after consuming 70$ worth of dishes.  The Jumbo mango prawns - They were not terrible, however they did not remove the vein nor the outer shell?? I expected more for a 25 dollar dish.  The fried red snapper - Horrendous, The fish was encased in mush.. It was nauseating, the fish itself tasted like soap.  Just thinking back of the experience is making my stomach turn, This is not authentic Malaysian cuisine and they should have paid us to dine here.  Side note, The chop sticks are made of wood and are reused. We know this because they were served to us dirty, and with bite marks.  From what I understand, this venue used to be great until some sort of change happened and everything went downhill. It is clear the changes in the cooking staff.  Never again

A miserable experience at best. The service was below abysmal. The manager woman and the waitresses/ staff all seem like they are on edge about something. Shuffling around with really angry faces. The upside of the service is that when you're really hungry, your food comes out immediately. The downside is that it really comes out IMMEDIATELY. That means it could come before the appetizer, and it could mean that it could come out 15 minutes before the rest of the table gets their food. The staff can barely speak a word of english, and when you get your plate before the rest of the table, you've no idea when the rest of it is coming out.  We got some 'Prawn Mee' ("Nyonya's Favorite"), which tasted like salty- rotten fish soup. I understand it's a prawn soup, but believe me when I tell you, the soup was spoiled. Horribly bitter fishy- after taste, with a miserable attempt to be covered up by probably 3 tablespoons of chili powder per tablespoon of soup. Almost had a fizzy ness to it. We attempted to send it back to try the Java Mee, but they refuse to take it back. The manager came out - Angry asian woman- (In terrible broken english): YOU ORDAH PRAWN SOUP, IT TAST-UH SPICY YOU PAY! EVERYBODY GET-A THIS ONE AND THEY PAY, YOU PAY. YOU NO RETURN. YOU PAY. Me: Uh, miss. I've had prawn soup before, please taste it. It's spoiled. Manager: NO I DONT CARE, YOU PAY, YOU EAT. YOU NO RETURN. Turns around and walks back to the kitchen.  Sorry for the word salad. This was just a very upsetting experience. I've never gotten so angry in a restaurant before, and also never wrote a review, but i couldn't live this one down. Don't eat here, they're mean people with bad soup.
